<h4 id="1-1-1-non-text-content-a"><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/UNDERSTANDING-WCAG20/text-equiv-all.html">1.1.1 Non-text content (A)</a></h4>
<p>All non-text content like images, charts, icons and infographics, must have an appropriate text equivalent. This ensures that information conveyed by non-text content is available to people who cannot see it, like screen reader users.</p>
<h5 id="requirements-what-to-do">Requirements / What to do?</h5>
<ul>
<li>  Images (like logos and icons) that communicate information have short text descriptions;</li>
<li>  Editorial images that support the text around them have short descriptions;</li>
<li>  Images (like infographics, charts and diagrams) that communicate complex information also have longer text descriptions within the same page;</li>
<li>  Decorative images have empty text descriptions.</li>
</ul>
<h5 id="common-mistakes">Common mistakes</h5>
<ul>
<li>  The image communicates information but does not have a text description;</li>
<li>  The text description does not communicate the same information as the image;</li>
<li>  The image has a text description but, like a placeholder or file name, it does not communicate the information in the image;</li>
<li>  The image has a text description that is an exact duplication of content elsewhere on the page.</li>
</ul>
